04929nam a22006615i 9780271061214DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20212013pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710612147 a10.1515/97802710612142doi  a(DE-B1597)583801  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aB945.R234bS35 2013eb 7aPHI0020002bisacsh04a1912231 aSciabarra, Chris Matthew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAyn Rand :bThe Russian Radical /cChris Matthew Sciabarra. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2013  a1 online resource (544 p.) :b17 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface to the Second Edition -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart one: The process of becoming -- t1 Synthesis in Russian Culture -- t2 Lossky, the Teacher -- t3 Educating Alissa -- t4 The Maturation of Ayn Rand -- tPart two: The revolt against dualism -- t5 Being -- t6 Knowing -- t7 Reason and Emotion -- t8 Art, Philosophy, and Efficacy -- t9 Ethics and Human Survival -- t10 A Libertarian Politics -- tPart three: The radical rand -- t11 Relations of Power -- t12 The Predatory State -- t13 History and Resolution -- tEpilogue -- tAppendix I: The Rand Transcript (1999) -- tAppendix II: The Rand Transcript, Revisited (2005) -- tAppendix III: A Challenge to Russian Radical- and Ayn Rand (2013) -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAuthor of The Fountainhead and Atlas Shrugged, Ayn Rand (1905-1982) is one of the most widely read philosophers of the twentieth century. Yet, despite the sale of over thirty million copies of her works, there have been few serious scholarly examinations of her thought. Ayn Rand: The Russian Radical provides a comprehensive analysis of the intellectual roots and philosophy of this controversial thinker. It has been nearly twenty years since the original publication of Chris Sciabarra's Ayn Rand: The Russian Radical. Those years have witnessed an explosive increase in Rand sightings across the social landscape: in books on philosophy, politics, and culture; in film and literature; and in contemporary American politics, from the rise of the Tea Party to recent presidential campaigns. During this time Sciabarra continued to work toward the reclamation of the dialectical method in the service of a radical libertarian politics, culminating in his book Total Freedom: Toward a Dialectical Libertarianism (Penn State, 2000). In this new edition of Ayn Rand, Chris Sciabarra adds two chapters that present in-depth analysis of the most complete transcripts to date documenting Rand's education at Petrograd State University. A new preface places the book in the context of Sciabarra's own research and the recent expansion of interest in Rand's philosophy. Finally, this edition includes a postscript that answers a recent critic of Sciabarra's historical work on Rand. Shoshana Milgram, Rand's biographer, has tried to cast doubt on Rand's own recollections of having studied with the famous Russian philosopher N. O. Lossky. Sciabarra shows that Milgram's analysis fails to cast doubt on Rand's recollections-or on Sciabarra's historical thesis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aDialectic. 0aObjectivism (Philosophy). 0aPhilosopherszRussia. 0aPhilosopherszUnited States. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271061214423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271061214.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn St